    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_903140113" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/903140113" />
    <a title="Mackenzie Corpora" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/30328717-mackenzie-corpora"><img alt="Mackenzie Corpora" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/903140113?book_show_action=true">Apr 06, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mackenzie Corpora" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mackenzie Corpora" href="/user/show/30328717-mackenzie-corpora">Mackenzie Corpora</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer903140113" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10018204975114676820">I picked up the book and was captured immediately from the first page and forward, it was a book that i found myself not being able to put down. Right from the start Finding Sagrado has done something that I have yet to see. It’s almost like a premonition for how the readers, myself included, act after picking up this book. Shane is so lost in his own book that by the next morning he’s still thinking about it constantly. <br/>Then the heavy stuff comes and after reading this you realize the emotional</span>
  <span id="freeText10018204975114676820" style="display:none">I picked up the book and was captured immediately from the first page and forward, it was a book that i found myself not being able to put down. Right from the start Finding Sagrado has done something that I have yet to see. It’s almost like a premonition for how the readers, myself included, act after picking up this book. Shane is so lost in his own book that by the next morning he’s still thinking about it constantly. <br />Then the heavy stuff comes and after reading this you realize the emotional struggle of a runaway teenager. This is a book that I believe all teenager readers can really relate too. I’d like to go as far as to say even adults who were once teenagers could relate to this. <br />Shane navigates through this world and is starting to learn things and make decisions for himself. His religious views are expanding and he’s learning to understand about a different lifestyle then his own. <br />This book brings up many topics that as teenagers are controversial but something that we experience. Learning about our own sexuality, broadening our horizons, maturity, and what it means to be youthful and free. <br />As a girl I would also highly recommend this book to every girl because of the character Viola Sanchez. She’s a wonderful role model, something a lot of books sometimes lack, for all girls; especially of Hispanic descent. <br />This book explores the deepest part of a teenager and I believe there are more underlying messages through the book that could be explored. This is the kind of story that is memorable and sticks with you. I would recommend this book to anyone looking for a well written coming of age story. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="10018204975114676820" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


